T1  - Policy impacts under rational expectations
AU  - F. Darrat, Ali
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 15
IS  - 2
SP  - 257
EP  - 271
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/04/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(91)90067-V
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669190067V
AB  - This paper re-examines for the U.S. the validity of the Macro Rational Expectations (MRE) hypothesis. In contrast to most previous studies in this area, the paper (a) considers the potential real effects of both monetary and fiscal policies, (b) allows for possible endogeneity of these policies, and (c) uses a joint, non-linear estimation methodology to distangle the hypothesis of rationality from that of neutrality. The empirical results reject the joint MRE hypothesis for both policies. The results also indicate that policy non-neutrality is the culprit behind such rejection. This evidence offers further empirical support for macro-rational expectations models where monetary and fiscal policies can, due to some rigidities, play a key role in stabilizing the real economy.
ER  - 

